POD1000000047_S0000080	Yeah, absolutely. And just a little bit more broadly, you know, the key idea behind Effector Altruism is that we want to try and figure out which altruistic activities, which charities, which career paths, which causes do the most good. And we think that being able to
POD1000000047_S0000081	measure things or at least trying to measure things is incredibly valuable in making progress on those questions. But obviously these are many of these questions are incredibly difficult to answer so a common criticism that we often get is people saying something like
POD1000000047_S0000082	oh it's impossible to figure out which charities or careers do the most good so you're wasting your tough trying and you should just go with your gut or you know help personal causes. What do you think of this kind of objection and do you think that there's anything to it?
POD1000000047_S0000083	you know, concern about there being too much uncertainty. You know, we often respond by saying that, you know, it doesn't mean that we shouldn't try and estimation is clearly the best we have. But yeah, what are your thoughts on this challenge? And
POD1000000047_S0000085	I mean this is not a comment that's just restricted to the area that you're talking about. It happens all the time. It used to happen in healthcare. People used to say, oh you can't put a value on a human life.
POD1000000047_S0000086	We've just got to do all we can to do good if we have to just go with our guts, essentially. That view now, certainly in the UK, has been completely discredited. You can put a value on a human life, we do, all the time.
POD1000000047_S0000087	Not sure everyone would agree, but...
POD1000000047_S0000088	Not for everyone you can agree and of course.
POD1000000047_S0000089	But you have to.
POD1000000047_S0000090	But NICE for example has been doing this for over a decade.
POD1000000047_S0000092	putting a value on the marginal benefit of a particular healthcare intervention and assessing what should be supported under the National Health Service according to these formal criteria. Now we know this is not perfect, we know this does not measure everything,
POD1000000047_S0000093	But it's explicit, it's transparent, and they've done their best, and I think it's been a massive success and a huge example to other countries as to how you can go about it. Now, we know it's never perfect, it's never perfect.
POD1000000047_S0000094	But, of course, people have been trying to take that approach, which I think has been extremely beneficial and healthy, and move it into other areas. Now, how can you do it so people are trying to do it with the environment? How can we measure the value of a tree? Well, people are trying to measure the value of a tree.
POD1000000047_S0000095	I don't know what the trees were, there was quite a lot.
POD1000000047_S0000097	working out all these different, trying to measure the benefit of a healthy, sustainable environment, etc. What's the value of a species?
POD1000000047_S0000098	It's too easy to sit back and say, oh you can't do it, you can't measure that. Well, you can have a good go. So as you say, it's always a balance between trying your best, realising you're never going to be able to do it,
POD1000000047_S0000099	but not to be put off having a good go. So it's like a lot of things we do in statistics, trying to measure things, trying to model things, that we always know what we do is inadequate, but that doesn't mean you can't do useful things.
POD1000000047_S0000101	Can you tell us a bit more about NICE and how they prioritise health treatments within the United Kingdom?
POD1000000047_S0000102	That's something I've worked on as a medical statistician. I've been a huge supporter of NICE. Essentially, what they do is when they decide whether to have a new vaccine or whether to decide to have a new recommended
POD1000000047_S0000103	for drugs to be paid for under the NHS, for example, they will look at what is the expected benefit of that intervention and what's the expected cost. And then they look at how much it's going to cost to
POD1000000047_S0000104	and provide an extra what they call a quality, a quality adjusted life year. So one year of life that's discounted if it's poor quality, you will, you know, you'll discount it won't be worth the whole year. And then essentially they can make the comparison
POD1000000047_S0000105	and they look if something comes in at less than £20,000 a quali, it just almost is paid for, you know, just yep, fine, we'll pay for it under the NHS. If it's more than about £30,000, then they really try to
POD1000000047_S0000107	we don't want to pay for this.
POD1000000047_S0000108	and try to go back to the drug company to renegotiate a price, for example, between 20,000 and 30,000. Well, you know, that's more in the grey zone. So, and this has been enormously beneficial, partly
POD1000000047_S0000109	in order to go back to drug companies and get them to reduce their prices. But and also to see that some interventions, for example, cancer screening, come in extremely cheap. They're just worth doing. It also means you have to be explicit, for example, on how much you value the future
POD1000000047_S0000110	rather than the present because they put in a discount rate, currently 3.5%. Now that means that a year of life in 25 years time, for example, is only worth about half what a year of life now is worth. And that's taken into account.
POD1000000047_S0000111	And now that of course is controversial. And if we're talking about big policy decisions for example about climate change that's far too big a discount rate. We wouldn't care less about the world in 100 years time if we use that discount. So in different areas.
POD1000000047_S0000112	you might be wanting to use a different disk. But these are taking economic ideas and moving them into very human decisions.
POD1000000047_S0000113	and I think they are enormously helpful and illuminating, but they're never perfect.
POD1000000047_S0000115	Yeah, I've actually written an article with Professor Toby Ord about why we shouldn't discount health, even though we should discount financial returns, about why it's appropriate in one case and not in the other. So we'll put up a link to that on the website.
POD1000000047_S0000116	A lot of people who are planning out their careers, they feel just overwhelmed by uncertainty. They don't know how much they're going to earn in one career, or what's the chances of getting into academia, or being elected to parliament.
POD1000000047_S0000117	How do you think people ought to make decisions when they're just surrounded by so much uncertainty?
POD1000000047_S0000118	Well, I mean you could say that we're always surrounded by this again, this is common to everything we do. We never know what's going to happen in the future, which is great. People don't want to know what's going to happen in the future. People don't even know what they're going to get for Christmas, let alone what's going to happen for the rest of their lives.
POD1000000047_S0000119	And so this is just a common problem. And we need to distinguish what we might call risk and uncertainty. Risk is when it's a very well defined problem, short term issues, buying lottery tickets when we know what the chances are.
POD1000000047_S0000120	then we can sort of take a rational approach. When we're dealing with deeper uncertainty, when we're really not even sure what the options are, how our lives might develop, then it's very difficult to take a completely formal approach. And so I wouldn't
POD1000000047_S0000121	try to say, oh, we should be able to do all this mathematically at all. However, the basics, those qualitative ideas of thinking through a rational decision are still very valuable because you think of, you know, what are the options available?
POD1000000047_S0000122	what are the possibilities and what are the possible consequences of what I might do. Now, that's always inadequate. You're never going to be able to think of everything. However, by thinking through that, some things might become immediately apparent, some immediate rankings of
POD1000000047_S0000123	what is preferable and not preferable might become apparent. And otherwise, we might need to fall back on broader strategies for making decisions in the face of
POD1000000047_S0000124	what we call deeper uncertainty. This is a deeply contested area. When governments make policies, very often they're in these situations where they can't even think of all the things that might happen. So they're in this situation of deeper uncertainty.
POD1000000047_S0000125	and people have suggested various ways to go about it. The first thing is not to think that you can optimize. You can't be perfect. You cannot be perfect. So the sort of suggestions that people make in terms of general decision making in these contexts
POD1000000047_S0000126	So to do with flexibility and resilience, that you want to be, you don't want to commit yourself to something you're not going to be able to change because you can't predict everything that's going to happen. So you're going to build in flexibility and adaptivity to your decision.
POD1000000047_S0000127	That's the same in any business, any government, any project at all. The other thing is to build in resilience in which you essentially can cope with the unexpected. That means both the possibility of really good things happening
POD1000000047_S0000128	as well as the possibility of really bad things happening. You are making sure that you haven't put all your eggs in one basket, essentially, so if something goes wrong, you haven't completely gone up a total blind alley that you can't renegotiate.
POD1000000047_S0000129	which means operating from the most robust basis as possible. So it means not trying to optimise the single path, but building in robustness, which means, I think in terms of career, of course, building in
POD1000000047_S0000130	transferable skills that you're going to be able to use in a variety of circumstances. So I think these are standard tactics for responding to deeper uncertainty, which can be used in any situation.
POD1000000047_S0000132	Yeah, that's definitely something that the organisation 80,000 Hours who advise people on how to have a big impact with their careers really focus on, especially early in your career, keep your options open, choose things that are robust under lots of different possible things happening.
POD1000000047_S0000134	One other question that we find we come up against a fair amount in thinking about careers and charities and all kinds of things is, you know, how do you go about choosing between a small chance of some really huge outcome, like, you know, saving the world from a pandemic that kills millions?
POD1000000047_S0000136	against some high probability of a very moderate or a more moderate outcome, so you know helping people in your local community. This seems like a very difficult thing to deal with. Do you have any thoughts on how people can go about making these kinds of decisions?
POD1000000047_S0000137	Yeah, very difficult, but again, these are common decisions always in our lives. Do we go for the high-risk option or the safer option? I personally think that
POD1000000047_S0000138	A mixed strategy is something that businesses would recommend, although I'm not involved in any investment decisions. Often, people would take an idea of a portfolio
POD1000000047_S0000139	of risk-taking, because these are all risks, you can't guarantee that you're going to do anything. You might have invested in rather safe things with a safe return, you're pretty sure that
POD1000000047_S0000140	what you're going to do is going to have a reasonable return and really you can predict the consequences of what you're using your career or your money for, what you're giving for. On the other hand, on more speculative
POD1000000047_S0000141	where you might be supporting something that actually might not come to anything either because the solution is promising.
POD1000000047_S0000142	won't work or the threat won't arise in the first place. So I think that's a mixed strategy in these circumstances. Again, you know, I wouldn't want to just put all the eggs in one basket.
POD1000000047_S0000144	I also personally feel that I quite like a mixed strategy in which some things are, the bigger
POD1000000047_S0000146	slightly anonymous.
POD1000000047_S0000147	where you're giving money
POD1000000047_S0000149	large organization is doing something which is contributing in a probably predictable way to improving things for people versus the more personal ones where you do have the personal
POD1000000047_S0000150	contact. And you might get a slightly more sort of emotional feedback from that, partly because that might encourage you to perhaps take on a more good feedback from the altruism, might encourage you to take on a bigger altruism.
POD1000000047_S0000151	a bigger commitment in the future.
POD1000000047_S0000153	So there are various ways of thinking about how to quantify the risks or possible gains associated with an activity. Can you explain what a micro-mort or a micro-life is?
