POD1000000048_S0000001	Hi, I'm Rob, Director of Research at 80,000 Hours. Today I'm speaking with Myles Brundage, Research Fellow at the University of Oxford's Future of Humanity Institute.
POD1000000048_S0000002	He studies the social implications surrounding the development of new technologies and has a particular interest in artificial general intelligence, that is, an AI system that could do most or all of the tasks humans could do.
POD1000000048_S0000003	Miles' research has been supported by the National Science Foundation, the Bipartisan Policy Centre and the Future of Life Institute. Thanks for making time to talk to us today, Miles.
POD1000000048_S0000004	Thanks for having me.
POD1000000048_S0000005	So first up, maybe just tell us a bit about your background and what questions you're looking into at the moment.
POD1000000048_S0000007	Sure. So I used to work on energy policy when I was living in Washington, DC, and I've gradually moved into AI policy over the past few years because it seems like it was more of a neglected area and could have a very large impact.
POD1000000048_S0000008	So I recently started at the Future of Humanity Institute and I'm also concurrently finishing up my PhD in Human and Social Dimensions of Science and Technology at Arizona State University.
POD1000000048_S0000009	So in both capacities, I am interested in what sorts of methods would be useful for thinking about AI in a rigorous way, and particularly the uncertainty of possible futures surrounding AI.
POD1000000048_S0000010	And I have a few more specific interests, such as openness and artificial intelligence and the risks related to bad actors.
POD1000000048_S0000011	Okay, so are you trying to predict what's going to happen and when and what sort of effects it will have?
POD1000000048_S0000012	So not necessarily predict per se, but at least understand what's plausible. I think that it's very difficult to predict with any high confidence what's going to happen and when.
POD1000000048_S0000013	but understanding, for example, what sorts of actions people could carry out with AI systems today or in the foreseeable future in different domains like cybersecurity,
POD1000000048_S0000014	and information operations, production of fake news automatically, and autonomous drones and so forth.
POD1000000048_S0000015	I think understanding the security landscape of those sorts of things doesn't necessarily require a very detailed forecast of when exactly something will occur so much as understanding what's technologically possible, given near-term trends.
POD1000000048_S0000017	You don't necessarily have to say this is when this particular accident or malicious behavior will occur, but just that these are the sorts of risks that we need to be prepared for.
POD1000000048_S0000018	Right, right. Does that bring you into contact with organizations that are developing AIs like Google?
POD1000000048_S0000020	Yeah, yeah, absolutely. So those organizations have an interest in making sure that AI is as beneficial as possible.
POD1000000048_S0000022	keenly aware of the fact that they can be misused and that there might be accident risks associated with them.
POD1000000048_S0000023	So, for example, I held a workshop fairly recently on the connection between bad actors and AI and what sorts of bad actors we might be concerned about in this space, and we had some participation from some of those groups.
POD1000000048_S0000024	Right, right. What kinds of bad actors are you thinking of?
POD1000000048_S0000025	I think there, you can look at it from a number of different perspectives. So depending on the domain that you're interested in, you might end up with different sorts of actors.
POD1000000048_S0000026	So in the case of physical harm associated with AI, you might look at autonomous weapons and the weaponization of consumer drones. And in that case, it's something that would be particularly appealing to state actors as well as terrorists.
POD1000000048_S0000027	We're already seeing the weaponization of consumer drones, though without much autonomy, if any, in the case of ISIS overseas.
POD1000000048_S0000028	So there are cases like that where we can foresee that particular groups with when given more advanced capabilities such as higher baseline levels of autonomy and consumer drones
POD1000000048_S0000029	would like, would be able to and would like to carry out damage on a larger scale.
POD1000000048_S0000030	But in other cases, it's less clear. So, for example, there are concerns around mass surveillance, and it's often not totally clear whether one should be more concerned about states or corporations.
POD1000000048_S0000031	depending on what sorts of risk you're concerned about. For example, corporations currently have a lot of data on people and
POD1000000048_S0000032	There's, there have been a lot of concerns raised about the use of AI to make decisions that have critical impacts on people's lives.
POD1000000048_S0000033	such as denying loans and court decisions and so forth that are being informed by often not very transparent algorithms.
POD1000000048_S0000034	So those are some concerns, but there's also a potentially different class of concerns around authoritarian states using AI for oppression.
POD1000000048_S0000035	So it's, I think there's a range of risks, but generally speaking, there's going to be a steady increase in the floor of the skill level as these AI technologies diffuse
POD1000000048_S0000036	That is, there will be more and more capabilities available to people at the bottom of the scale, that is individuals as well as people with more access to computing power and money and data at the higher end.
POD1000000048_S0000037	So it's not totally clear how to think about that because on the one hand you might expect that
POD1000000048_S0000038	The biggest actors are the most concerning because they have the most skill and resources. But on the other hand, they also are sometimes in the case of democratic governments,
POD1000000048_S0000039	held accountable to citizens and in the case of corporations held accountable to stakeholders. You might also think that you would be more concerned about individual rogue actors.
POD1000000048_S0000040	So that's an issue I'm still trying to think through in the context of the report that I'm writing based on that workshop.
POD1000000048_S0000041	Right. So people often distinguish between the short-term risks from AI, like self-driving cars not working properly or algorithmic bias.
POD1000000048_S0000042	and then the longer term concerns of what we're going to do once an artificial intelligence is as smart as humans or potentially much, much more intelligent. Which one of those do you spend more time working on?
POD1000000048_S0000043	I try to focus on issues that span different time horizons. So I think AI and security is something that we're already seeing some early instances of today.
POD1000000048_S0000044	So it's already being used for detection of cyber threats, for example, and the production of vulnerabilities in software. There's a lot of research going on.
POD1000000048_S0000045	with an example being the DARPA Cyber Grand Challenge recently, where there was automated hacking and automated defense.
POD1000000048_S0000046	So there's already stuff happening on the front of AI and security as well as the economics of AI and issues surrounding privacy.
POD1000000048_S0000047	But it's not totally clear whether the issues in the future will just be straightforward extensions of those or whether there will be qualitatively different
POD1000000048_S0000049	I think it's important to think about what's happening today and imagine how it might progressively develop into a more extreme future, as well as to think about possible discontinuities when AI progresses more quickly.
POD1000000048_S0000050	Right, right. So I should say at this point that we have a profile up on our website about the potential upsides and downsides of artificial intelligence where we go through all of the basics
POD1000000048_S0000051	And Miles, you have a forthcoming guide to work on AI policy and strategy that we're going to link to. So here we're going to try to go beyond that. So if you find yourself a little bit confused, then potentially just go and read one of those documents first.
POD1000000048_S0000052	So, which policy or strategy questions do you see as most important for us to answer in order to ensure that the development of artificial intelligence goes well rather than in a bad way?
POD1000000048_S0000053	I think there are a lot of questions and some of the ones I was talking about earlier surrounding security and preventing the weaponization of AI by dangerous actors is one.
POD1000000048_S0000054	But one, and there are also other issues that have been widely discussed in the media and by academics such as accountability of algorithms and transparency, the economic impacts of AI, and so forth.
POD1000000048_S0000055	But one that I think is particularly important, particularly over the long term, and this is a case where there might be a need to think about possible discontinuities,
POD1000000048_S0000056	is coordination surrounding AI safety. So there's been a lot of attention called to AI safety in the past few years, and there's starting to be a lot of concrete and successful research on the problem of avoiding certain AI safety failure modes.
POD1000000048_S0000057	like wireheading and value misalignment and so forth. But there's been less attention paid to how do you actually incentivize people to act on the best practices and the good theoretical frameworks that are developed.
POD1000000048_S0000058	assuming that they will be developed. And that's a potentially big problem if there's a competitive situation between companies or between countries or both, and there's an incentive to skimp on those safety measures.
POD1000000048_S0000059	So there's been a little bit of work, for example, by Armstrong et al at the Future of Humanity Institute, looking at arms race type scenarios involving AI where there would be an incentive to skimp.
POD1000000048_S0000060	because you're concerned about losing the lead in an AI race. And there might be significant, we don't really know what the extent will be.
POD1000000048_S0000061	but it might turn out that there are significant trade-offs between safety and performance of AI systems. So one might be tempted to, in order to gain an advantage, whether economic or military or intelligence-wise,
POD1000000048_S0000062	ramp up the capabilities of an AI system by adding more hardware, adding more data, adding more sensors and effectors and so forth. But that might actually be dangerous if you don't understand the full behavioral envelope of the system.
POD1000000048_S0000063	so to speak, and how to constrain actors, the human actors, from doing that is a very difficult problem.
POD1000000048_S0000064	So I've, I along with some others at the Future of Humanity Institute and others at different organizations have started thinking about what is an incentive compatible mechanism to ensure
POD1000000048_S0000065	that people do the right thing in that case. That is to say, we don't want to ask people to do something that's totally against their interests.
POD1000000048_S0000066	if they actually do have an interest in developing these systems and protecting themselves militarily or otherwise. But we also want to ensure that they're constrained in some sort of way.
POD1000000048_S0000067	So one example would be an arranged, this is not necessarily a fully fleshed out example, but just to illustrate the sort of thing I'm talking about.
POD1000000048_S0000068	would be some sort of arrangement between AI developers such that in order to gain access to the latest breakthroughs or the latest computing power,
POD1000000048_S0000069	you would need to submit to some sort of safety monitoring and adhere to certain best practices.
POD1000000048_S0000070	That would create an incentive if you want to be on the cutting edge to participate in those safety protocols. So again, that's not a fully worked out example.
POD1000000048_S0000071	but that's an example of the class of things that I would like to see more of. So developing specific proposals for how to ensure that the right thing that's being developed on the technical front actually gets implemented.
POD1000000048_S0000072	Right. Do you look much at, say, what governments should be doing in this area, whether there's regulations that we should be putting in place or at least preparing to put in place in future?
POD1000000048_S0000073	Yeah, so I think that that ties in with what I was saying a little bit in that one might envision that as AI capabilities develop,
POD1000000048_S0000074	that it will be increasingly seen as a matter of national security that a country be on the leading end. So I think it's not super clear how to navigate that yet.
POD1000000048_S0000075	I think there's some low-hanging fruit. So clearly, in my opinion, it would be beneficial for countries to have some experts in-house in their governments who actually know something about AI.
POD1000000048_S0000076	and are able to deal with crises as they arise, if they arise, and to be able to think carefully about the impacts of AI on the labor force, for example.
POD1000000048_S0000077	So I think there's some low-hanging fruit and some policies that have been developed for dealing with some of the near-term issues. But for the longer-term issues,
POD1000000048_S0000078	It's not super clear that we want to rush into a situation where governments are leading this, if that would turn out to only accentuate the arms race dynamics
POD1000000048_S0000079	that we should be trying to avoid if AI is seen even more as a national security issue in an unhelpful way.
POD1000000048_S0000080	So I think it's incumbent on those who are thinking about the long term policy issues around AI to develop a more positive proposal that involves not just
POD1000000048_S0000081	you know, the US government getting involved for the purpose of accelerating American AI capabilities.
POD1000000048_S0000082	but some more collaborative approach.
POD1000000048_S0000083	I suppose with previous dangerous technologies like nuclear weapons or chemical or biological weapons, there's been agreements to try to slow down their development and deployment. Is that something that could potentially happen here at the international level?
POD1000000048_S0000085	I think it's possible to imagine some sort of slowing down among a small number of actors
POD1000000048_S0000086	And we're fortunate that there is a high concentration of computing power and talent and skill in a fairly small number of organizations.
POD1000000048_S0000087	So there's pretty much no chance of some random person out competing the top organizations at AI in a surprising way.
POD1000000048_S0000088	So it's possible that with some of the top companies and non-profits as well as countries, they could coordinate in some sort of way.
POD1000000048_S0000089	not to postpone AI across society for a long period of time, but at least to be cautious in the later stages of development and to allow time for mutual vetting of safety procedures and things like that.
POD1000000048_S0000090	So I think it's possible to imagine some sort of coordination, but the technical and the political factors interact to a large extent.
POD1000000048_S0000091	to the extent that we actually have good safety measures that are efficient and that don't introduce a lot of overhead, computational or otherwise, into these systems.
POD1000000048_S0000092	then we'll be in a better place to actually get people to coordinate because it won't be imposing a lot of costs on them. And likewise, to the extent that we're able to coordinate better,
POD1000000048_S0000093	it will be in a better position to actually get people to implement those mechanisms if they do impose some performance penalty.
POD1000000048_S0000094	Right. So can you think of any major bits of progress we've made on AI strategy questions over the last couple of years?
POD1000000048_S0000095	So the example I mentioned of the paper by Armstrong et al. called the Race into the Precipice is one example and it presented sort of a stark version of the arms race scenario.
POD1000000048_S0000096	though I think there are reasons to be more optimistic than are presented in that paper, because they look at only a certain set of assumptions as with any model.
POD1000000048_S0000097	But more generally, I think there's been progress in the development of principles and criteria for good policies in recent years. So, for example, with the Asilomar conference and a set of Asilomar AI principles,
POD1000000048_S0000098	I think that was a good step towards developing some shared understanding around the need to avoid arms races and concerns over AI weaponization and so forth.
POD1000000048_S0000099	But it's, I still think that there's a lot of room for
POD1000000048_S0000100	progress to be made. So there was a paper put out by the Future of Humanity Institute by Nick Bostrom, Kirk Flynn, and Alan Defoe recently that looks at policy desiderata for the development of machine superintelligence.
POD1000000048_S0000101	And there's a lot of good material there, but I think they would be the first to admit that we're still at the high-level principle stage of developing these policies.
POD1000000048_S0000102	So we have a better understanding of what we want to avoid than we did a few years ago and what sorts of, what a good policy proposal would look like.
POD1000000048_S0000103	but we don't yet have anything super actionable. So I think the situation is a bit analogous to where AI safety was a few years ago.
POD1000000048_S0000104	where there was starting to be an articulation of what the problem was with the book Superintelligence and various other publications.
POD1000000048_S0000105	And people were starting to take the problem seriously and started to have a vocabulary for what a solution would look like with value alignment and other terms being coined.
POD1000000048_S0000106	But there wasn't yet any concrete research agenda and subsequently there have been a lot of concrete research agendas as well.
POD1000000048_S0000107	well as technical progress on some parts of those research agendas with work by OpenAI and DeepMind and others leading the way.
POD1000000048_S0000108	So I think that we're potentially in a similarly exciting phase on the AI policy front where we have a decent understanding of what the problem is. And with the example of avoiding arms races being forefront in my mind,
POD1000000048_S0000109	least, but we don't yet have a concrete, we don't have clear models and case studies that we can point to as ways forward.
POD1000000048_S0000110	So I think that's the next step is moving into more concrete proposals and trying to balance some of the trade-offs that have been identified in recent papers.
POD1000000048_S0000112	So it seems like a lot of the latest thinking in this area isn't written up in public yet, partly because people don't want to publicize their views at this point or just because it takes a long time to get papers published.
POD1000000048_S0000113	What do you think is the best way for someone who's interested in working in the area to get up to speed on the issues?
POD1000000048_S0000114	So I think, again, it's somewhat analogous to the situation with AI safety a few years ago. And I think the book Superintelligence was a big step forward on that front in terms of having a single reference to point people to.
POD1000000048_S0000115	But it's less clear if there's one single reference point people to on AI policy issues, though I'm hoping that the career guide that I'm working on will be somewhat useful in that regard.
POD1000000048_S0000116	Another resource that comes to mind is a syllabus for a class on the global politics of AI developed by Alan Defoe at Yale and the Future of Humanity Institute.
POD1000000048_S0000117	So that's a very detailed list of resources. And I'm sure there'll be a link provided for this interview somewhere.
POD1000000048_S0000118	Yeah.
POD1000000048_S0000119	And yeah, so I think that's another set of resources. So it's essentially a long list of both formal academic publications as well as things in the more gray literature.
POD1000000048_S0000120	such as blog posts, which is, you know, I think the sort of thing you're referring to is, you know, things that aren't necessarily written up academically, but are, you know, somewhat accessible. But even there, there's still some things like, you know, Google Docs that are used internally and so forth.
POD1000000048_S0000121	So I think if, if, if based on reading those sorts of things, this is clearly something you're interested in, then the obvious next step is just to get in touch with people who are working on these issues and ask and, you know, indicate what your interests are.
POD1000000048_S0000122	there might be things that aren't available online that they can point you to.
POD1000000048_S0000123	Yeah, you mentioned the Asilomar Statement of Principles, do you just want to describe that?
POD1000000048_S0000124	Sure.
POD1000000048_S0000125	Two years ago, there was a conference on beneficial AI held in Puerto Rico, and that led to an open letter on AI.
POD1000000048_S0000126	and subsequently some investment by Elon Musk in the Future of Life Institute, which supported a lot of grants in this space.
POD1000000048_S0000127	And I think that that led to a lot of attention to the issue and there were thousands of people, including a lot of scientists who signed on to that letter.
POD1000000048_S0000128	And then subsequently the Asilomar AI principles, which were developed at a conference two years later this year at Asilomar in California.
POD1000000048_S0000129	developed a more specific set of proposals for what sorts of things AI scientists should be thinking about. So not just the fact that there should be more research, but also things like capability cautions.
POD1000000048_S0000130	So being attentive to the fact that we don't know for sure what the upper limits of AI capabilities will ultimately be.
POD1000000048_S0000131	and the things I mentioned about avoiding arms races and being concerned about AI weaponization more broadly. So I think that's a good example of developing, you know, sort of a consensus view on what
POD1000000048_S0000132	What we want to see and what we don't want to see we want to see benefiting society as a whole and we don't want to see it leading to the occurring of benefits to a small number of people or to large scale war or anything like that.
POD1000000048_S0000133	And I think it's encouraging to see not just that, but also the development of other sets of principles through the IEEE and their effort on ethically aligned AI design.
POD1000000048_S0000134	So I read those principles and they seemed quite strong on paper. Do you think people are likely to follow through on them?
POD1000000048_S0000135	I think there's somewhat of a gap between the level of abstraction of the principles and concrete steps that people can take.
POD1000000048_S0000136	So, for example, it's not totally clear what any individual can can do to stop an arms race, for example, but I think it's a step in the right direction to know where where you're headed at
POD1000000048_S0000137	And then figuring out exactly what to do about that is the next step.
POD1000000048_S0000138	So in your guide, you suggest that people could potentially work on AI strategy and policy questions at places like Google DeepMind or OpenAI where artificial intelligence is actually being developed.
POD1000000048_S0000139	What concretely could you see people doing at places like that if they took a job there?
POD1000000048_S0000140	Yeah, so to some extent, people at those organizations are doing something fairly similar to what I and my colleagues are doing in academia, which is
POD1000000048_S0000141	which is thinking about what the problems are and trying to develop solutions. I think the benefit of being on that side of things is to have more direct exposure to what's happening on the ground, so to speak.
POD1000000048_S0000142	in AI development, and I think that can be useful for developing a set of what sorts of problems are actually cropping up as a result of the development of capabilities that actually exist as opposed to just ones in the future.
POD1000000048_S0000143	Though I think it's also notable that people at these organizations have been very active in the efforts that I've mentioned, such as raising attention to AI safety,
POD1000000048_S0000144	which was an initiative that involved people at Google Brain and OpenAI and the concrete problems and AI safety paper.
POD1000000048_S0000145	And people at DeepMind have been very influential in calling for more AI safety work, and they've been publishing fairly early on this matter relative to other organizations.
POD1000000048_S0000146	So I think there's a lot of reason to think that these organizations are playing a positive role and I think it's, it would be a good place to be involved in sort of thought, thought leadership on these topics.
POD1000000048_S0000147	as well as doing direct research.
POD1000000048_S0000149	And how hard is it to get a job at a place like that?
POD1000000048_S0000151	I would imagine they would only have a few people working on AI strategy or policy. Are these extremely competitive roles?
POD1000000048_S0000152	I would say they're pretty competitive. And I think that's a general phenomenon in anything related to AI these days, whether on the policy side or the technical side.
POD1000000048_S0000153	But I think that this is a growth area for sure. So if one develops expertise in this topic and has something to contribute to it,
POD1000000048_S0000154	then I think there will ultimately be opportunities available to you in the next few years.
POD1000000048_S0000155	It's again I want to draw an analogy to AI safety where there was a lot of concern about, you know, will there be jobs and AI safety, you know, three years or so ago and I think that deterred some grad students from working in this space.
POD1000000048_S0000156	And now the situation seems to look a bit better in that there's a fair number of advertisements for postdocs and people being hired at top labs to work on these issues.
POD1000000048_S0000157	So I think we'll probably see something pretty similar, not necessarily it becoming not competitive, but there being a little bit of slackening over time as there's a need for developing larger teams to work on these topics.
POD1000000048_S0000159	And another path you've talked about is going into politics or policy roles, for example as a congressional staffer or perhaps at a think tank like the Brookings Institute or the National Science Foundation or potentially just going into party politics in general.
POD1000000048_S0000160	What useful things do you envisage people could do there?
POD1000000048_S0000162	Yes, so I think in the same way that working at an AI lab would give you a better sense of what's practical on the technical front,
POD1000000048_S0000163	working for Congress or Parliament or a political party would give you a better sense of what's practical on the political front.
POD1000000048_S0000164	So in addition to that, developing a better intuition for the system that you're dealing with and what the constraints are.
POD1000000048_S0000165	I think it's also potentially a good way to actually influence what's actually done by those bodies.
POD1000000048_S0000166	So for example, in the US Congress right now, there was just recently announced an AI caucus to organize the discussion of members of Congress on issues related to AI.
POD1000000048_S0000167	with particular focus on issues related to the future of work, but I think over time we'll see more discussion of the longer term sorts of issues.
POD1000000048_S0000168	That we've been talking about in in those four and it would be useful to have people who are concerned about making sure that the right thing is is ultimately done working in those places.
POD1000000048_S0000169	able to actually act on the best current understanding developed by researchers and by practitioners.
POD1000000048_S0000170	Yeah. So I think a big risk of going into politics or policy in general would be that your career progresses but you're not specifically in one of the places that ends up having a say in how these things go.
POD1000000048_S0000171	You just end up being, working in a congressional committee that turns out not to be that relevant. Are there any roles that you can take early on or what can you do to position yourself well so that you don't just get sidelined in the end?
POD1000000048_S0000173	I think if you intend to work in politics, then you have to be somewhat opportunistic about jobs and the ebb and flow of political opportunities. So, for example,
POD1000000048_S0000174	If one congressional committee is declining in its relevance in terms of AI, then one should consider about jumping ship towards somewhere that's more relevant.
POD1000000048_S0000175	So I don't think that taking one particular job will lock you in forever, but building up some political capital and some human capital in that area could be useful.
POD1000000048_S0000176	Even if you ultimately want to switch to a different organization, but I would push back a little bit on the idea of, you know, not not being relevant just because you're not at the on the side of people.
POD1000000048_S0000177	You're not at the organization where people are developing the latest AI. I mean, as I mentioned before, I think that's a very exciting opportunity. And along with academia, it's a great place to work on these issues.
POD1000000048_S0000178	But governments still play an important role in framing these issues and in convening discussions.
POD1000000048_S0000179	So an example of this would be the Preparing for the Future of Artificial Intelligence report put out by the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy last year.
POD1000000048_S0000180	which was the result of four workshops that brought together experts in a wide variety of areas in law, economics, AI technology, and safety.
POD1000000048_S0000181	And so I think you still have an opportunity to frame the discussion and move the ball forward, even if you're not working in the latest labs.
POD1000000048_S0000182	Yeah. So what would be some of the best places to apply to in that area?
POD1000000048_S0000183	So it's a bit tricky to answer that in general. It depends on factors like what your citizenship is and what particular policy issues you're interested in.
POD1000000048_S0000184	But some fairly robust recommendations would be to look for a particular class of people that have technical backgrounds.
POD1000000048_S0000185	One area to look at would be AAAS fellowships. So the American Association for the Advancement of Science has a fellowship program
POD1000000048_S0000186	where they essentially put people in rotations in organizations like Congress and the executive branch where they can implement some of some of they can, you know, draw on their technical experience.
POD1000000048_S0000187	and someone with a background in AI would probably end up in an AI relevant organization. So I've heard a lot of good things about that being a good way to develop career capital and experience and understanding of how the political system works.
POD1000000048_S0000188	But that's not necessarily going to result in being in the exact right location for solving AI policy problems the next few months.
POD1000000048_S0000189	I think it's really hard to say where that would be, or even if there is such a place, because I think we're still
POD1000000048_S0000190	despite all the progress that's being made in a relatively early stage. So there isn't even yet a nomination for the Director of the Office of Science and Technology Policy in the White House
POD1000000048_S0000191	So, otherwise, I would say that that is a good place to go. So, and likewise, we don't really know what the agenda of the Trump administration is on the AI front.
POD1000000048_S0000192	And there's a lot of discussion, but not much institution building in governments at the moment. So it's hard for me to answer that in general.
POD1000000048_S0000193	but I think getting experience is a pretty robust thing to do.
POD1000000048_S0000194	Right. So a situation that I encounter reasonably often is I meet someone who's really smart, who is very interested in this topic, who might be able to make a great contribution.
POD1000000048_S0000195	But at the moment, there aren't that many groups that are hiring for these roles. So, you're at the Future of Humanity Institute and I guess there's also the Future of Life Institute. But there aren't that many places that someone can potentially apply.
POD1000000048_S0000196	So I'm thinking what advice should I give someone in that situation? Should they continue studying perhaps or building expertise so that they're in a better position to apply in future when the number of positions grows?
POD1000000048_S0000197	Yeah, I mean, again, it's hard to answer that in general. It depends on what
POD1000000048_S0000198	background the person has and what sorts of jobs are interested in. But I think if one casts a fairly large net in terms of what AI issues one wants to work on, there's a fairly large range of organizations.
POD1000000048_S0000199	It's not just FHI, there's also the Center for the Study of Existential Risk, the Leverhulme Center for the Future of Intelligence, the Tech Policy Lab at the University of Washington.
POD1000000048_S0000200	And, you know, various faculty programs around the various academic programs around the country in the US and around the world are looking to hire people.
POD1000000048_S0000201	for example, as postdocs or a faculty member in areas related to AI and policy if you're someone with an academic background.
POD1000000048_S0000202	and there are probably a fair number of policy positions at tech companies that aren't necessarily specific to AI, but that would lead to getting valuable experience in the broad area of tech policies.
POD1000000048_S0000203	So again, one, I guess to generalize a bit, I would recommend casting a fairly large net and working in adjacent areas if you can't immediately work in the exact right place.
POD1000000048_S0000204	Because this is not the sort of area where people have been working on AI policy for decades and it's hard to break in for that reason. It's more just that it's still a field that's growing.
POD1000000048_S0000205	And I don't think that that growth will stop. So I think there will be more opportunities in the future. But if you can't find the right opportunity now,
POD1000000048_S0000206	then again, talk to people in the field about what sorts of opportunities are on the horizon and try and work in adjacent fields. That might be one thing to consider.
POD1000000048_S0000207	Yeah, so what do you think would be the biggest challenges for someone sitting out trying to start a career in this area?
POD1000000048_S0000208	Depending on one's background, I think the main challenge would be boning up on areas of weakness.
POD1000000048_S0000209	So for example, if you have a policy background, you might want to focus on learning more about AI. And if you have a technical background, you might want to focus more on learning about policy.
POD1000000048_S0000210	I think one of the challenges is what you mentioned before about there not being a super clearly accessible literature on the topic.
