YOU1000000002_S0000000	This video was made possible by CuriosityStream. When you sign up at the link in the description, you'll also get access to Nebula, the streaming video platform that Wendover is a part of.
YOU1000000002_S0000001	The Wuhan coronavirus began, like all new viruses, with a remarkably ordinary moment.
YOU1000000002_S0000002	In late November 2019, someone—it is not yet known who—ate a wild animal that, by chance, carried the novel coronavirus
YOU1000000002_S0000003	and days later, started to feel the symptoms of what initially seemed like a bad cold.
YOU1000000002_S0000004	From there, more individuals were infected—at first through the consumption of other wild animals, but later through direct human-to-human transmission.
YOU1000000002_S0000005	For the entire month of December, the virus was there, in Wuhan, spreading, but nobody knew it.
YOU1000000002_S0000006	The cases, presenting as pneumonia, were at first considered to be caused by any one of the countless other viruses that can create such symptoms
YOU1000000002_S0000007	But eventually, the escalation in cases, and the fact that almost all the first patients had bought food at one particular wild animal market, caught the Wuhan city government's attention.
YOU1000000002_S0000008	The first official confirmation that something was up came on New Year's Eve.
YOU1000000002_S0000009	December 31st, when the Municipal Health Commission published a press release acknowledging the situation.
YOU1000000002_S0000010	over a month after the first transmission. At the time, this was small, local news.
YOU1000000002_S0000011	only a few dozen cases of pneumonia in a city of millions, in a country of a billion.
YOU1000000002_S0000012	But then came the news that this was not one of the many pre-existing pneumonia-causing viruses.
YOU1000000002_S0000013	This was something new. Western media first reported on the novel coronavirus around January 8th.
YOU1000000002_S0000014	The New York Times, forebodingly, wrote, "...there is no evidence that the new virus is readily spread by humans, and it has not been tied to any deaths."
YOU1000000002_S0000015	That would soon change.
YOU1000000002_S0000016	On January 21, when the World Health Organization started tracking the outbreak, there were 282 cases.
YOU1000000002_S0000017	The next day, 314. The next, 581.
YOU1000000002_S0000018	than 846, than 1,320,
YOU1000000002_S0000019	than 2014, and by the start of the week of January 26, it was clear that this would not be a quick and painless virus.
YOU1000000002_S0000020	This would be one for the history books, and it was going to get a lot worse before it got any better.
YOU1000000002_S0000021	Drastic circumstances called for drastic action. It was clear, given the trends, that Wuhan's hospitals would soon be overwhelmed by patients
YOU1000000002_S0000022	and, in the case of highly infectious viruses like coronavirus, that makes a bad situation worse as infected individuals will try to recover at home.
YOU1000000002_S0000023	where the virus can more easily spread. Therefore, the decision was made, on January 23rd, to build a brand new facility capable of treating 1,000 patients at once.
YOU1000000002_S0000024	It was announced that this would be done, fully constructed, by February 2nd.
YOU1000000002_S0000025	just 10 days later.
YOU1000000002_S0000026	China has experience with such a feat. In 2003, the country suffered an outbreak of severe acute respiratory syndrome, or SARS, which is also caused by a form of coronavirus.
YOU1000000002_S0000027	Much like with the novel coronavirus, hospitals were overwhelmed and many had to turn away patients.
YOU1000000002_S0000028	In response, the government decided to build a new hospital.
YOU1000000002_S0000029	Over six days, 7,000 construction workers brought the Xiaotongshan Hospital into reality and it quickly began accepting patients and relieving the overstressed medical system.
YOU1000000002_S0000030	Once the outbreak settled down, the Shaotongshan Hospital was hailed as a massive success by both the country itself and the World Health Organization.
YOU1000000002_S0000031	The statistics speak for themselves—overall, SARS had a fatality rate of 9.6%.
YOU1000000002_S0000032	At the Xiaochunshan Hospital, just 1.2% of patients died.
YOU1000000002_S0000033	and not a single staff member was infected.
YOU1000000002_S0000034	It's no wonder why China wanted to replicate this.
YOU1000000002_S0000035	and therefore Xiaotongshan was the model for the new coronavirus hospital, but this time would be different.
YOU1000000002_S0000036	The 2003 hospital began construction over six months after the beginning of the outbreak.
YOU1000000002_S0000037	The 2020 hospital started construction less than two months after the first case and just days after the seriousness of the outbreak became clear.
YOU1000000002_S0000038	There was far less time for planning and design. The orders came, and then it was immediately time to start.
YOU1000000002_S0000039	Step one was finding a place to put the hospital.
YOU1000000002_S0000040	The location selected was previously just an open field about 14 miles or 22 kilometers from central Wuhan.
YOU1000000002_S0000041	This kept it away from the dense urban core, where further transmission might be easier, but the field in question was also right off a large pre-existing road which made access easy.
YOU1000000002_S0000042	That road was quickly shut down and turned into, essentially, a parking lot and staging area for the project.
YOU1000000002_S0000043	The contract for this project was given to China Construction 3rd Engineering Bureau Company, a subsidiary of the state-owned China State Construction Engineering Corporation.
YOU1000000002_S0000044	By revenue, this is the world's largest construction company and it has experience in enormous projects like Beijing's new airport, Egypt's new capital city, and Tesla's Shanghai Gigafactory.
YOU1000000002_S0000045	If anyone was going to pull this off, it was them.
YOU1000000002_S0000046	To begin construction in earnest, they first needed to prepare the selected site.
YOU1000000002_S0000047	That involved, first, cutting down all the trees and shrubbery and then perfectly leveling the ground.
YOU1000000002_S0000048	Out of the 10-day construction timeline, this took longer than one might think.
YOU1000000002_S0000049	about 48 hours.
YOU1000000002_S0000050	This was due in part to the fact that the project was significantly understaffed in its first few days.
YOU1000000002_S0000051	as they scramble to find workers, especially as its start coincided with Chinese New Year's.
YOU1000000002_S0000052	Once the land was leveled, though, they moved on to constructing the building foundations by Sunday, January 26.
YOU1000000002_S0000053	For this, they used a layered system.
YOU1000000002_S0000054	On the bottom, an 8 inch or 20 centimeter layer of sand was placed, then what's referred to as a geotextile layer,
YOU1000000002_S0000055	a form of fabric, then a layer of waterproof plastic, then another geotextile layer, then another layer of sand.
YOU1000000002_S0000056	On that, they then poured concrete, which dried over a few days.
YOU1000000002_S0000057	But then came the truly impressive element.
YOU1000000002_S0000058	constructing the buildings themselves in a matter of days.
YOU1000000002_S0000059	What made this possible was the use of prefabricated elements.
YOU1000000002_S0000060	Modular construction such as this has been on the rise recently.
YOU1000000002_S0000061	It's now a well-established technique for the construction of buildings large and small.
YOU1000000002_S0000062	The idea is, simply, that somewhere off-site a number of identical building elements are built.
YOU1000000002_S0000063	Then, they're shipped to the construction site and put together.
YOU1000000002_S0000064	This has plenty of advantages.
YOU1000000002_S0000065	First and foremost, the use of identical elements, built in a factory system, to construct a larger building lowers costs through economies of scale.
YOU1000000002_S0000066	Then, when you actually get to putting the building together, on-site construction time is significantly less.
YOU1000000002_S0000067	which once again lowers cost.
YOU1000000002_S0000068	In this case, though, cost was not the primary concern.
YOU1000000002_S0000069	Speed-wise, and modular construction is the fastest way to build.
YOU1000000002_S0000070	Most of the site used a type of prefabricated, modular construction common with temporary buildings.
YOU1000000002_S0000071	While it's not clear which company produced the prefabricated components, it is clear that they existed before the project started.
YOU1000000002_S0000072	The first building elements started coming together on Monday, January 27th, just four days after the project broke ground.
YOU1000000002_S0000073	They began by building the skeleton of the modular units.
YOU1000000002_S0000074	Each of these units was about the shape and size of a 20-foot shipping container
YOU1000000002_S0000075	and this skeleton form included just the floor, ceiling, and structural supports at each corner.
YOU1000000002_S0000076	Throughout this all, separate teams, out of the thousands of workers there, started to hook the site up to utilities like sewage, water, electricity, and internets.
YOU1000000002_S0000077	Much of this just involved bringing in the state-owned companies responsible for these, but for internets, and the subsequent building out of an IT system, private companies like Huawei and Lenovo got involved.
YOU1000000002_S0000078	This was, no doubt, partially because the construction of this hospital drew considerable public attention in China.
YOU1000000002_S0000079	It came to represent the physical manifestation of the country's response to the crisis and also of China's engineering might.
YOU1000000002_S0000080	The construction process itself was streamed by state-owned broadcasting companies, and up to 18 million concurrent viewers watched the process.
YOU1000000002_S0000081	Nearly every major broadcaster in China reported from the site, publishing footage like what you're seeing now, although very few western broadcasters were there.
YOU1000000002_S0000082	This is part of the reason limited detailed information and footage of the construction exists outside of China's state-owned broadcasters.
YOU1000000002_S0000083	where the government can manage the story and what gets out.
YOU1000000002_S0000084	It was, no doubt, viewed as an opportunity by the Chinese government in a time when it faced intense criticism for its initial response to the outbreak.
YOU1000000002_S0000085	But, of course, to gain that praise, the project needed to be successful.
YOU1000000002_S0000086	On Tuesday, January 28th, significant portions of the first building were completed, while the rest of the complex's foundations were finishing up.
YOU1000000002_S0000087	Over the 29th and 30th, more of the overall structure came to be as the walls were installed on and in the skeletons of buildings, and work then began on turning these empty buildings into a hospital.
YOU1000000002_S0000088	Each patient room was outfitted with two beds, some medical equipment, and a bathroom.
YOU1000000002_S0000089	Considering the hospital is built with quarantine in mind, there are some unique aspects to the design of these rooms.
YOU1000000002_S0000090	For one, the ventilation system is built to keep negative pressure in all quarantine areas so that air will go out through an exhaust system rather than out under the door into the rest of the hospital.
YOU1000000002_S0000091	While at the time of writing it's not entirely known to what extent this coronavirus can spread through airborne transmission, a ventilation system like this is standard practice for any quarantine ward.
YOU1000000002_S0000092	In addition to individual patient rooms, separate areas were designed for patient processing, diagnostic tools like CT scanners were installed, and other crucial aspects like offices, break rooms, and canteens were built in.
YOU1000000002_S0000093	Over the 31st of January and 1st and 2nd of February, the final areas of the complex were built up, the interior installation was ramped up, and all the systems were tested to assure that the hospital was ready to bring in patients.
YOU1000000002_S0000094	Meanwhile, eight People's Liberation Army transport planes landed at Wuhan airport carrying the military medical staff who had staffed the hospital.
YOU1000000002_S0000095	They moved into the facility throughout the same day, February 2nd, then throughout the night, workers put the finishing touches onto the hundreds of rooms.
YOU1000000002_S0000096	Then, the next morning, the moment that ten days prior seemed impossible arrived.
YOU1000000002_S0000097	The first patients, transferred from other facilities, were wheeled into Houshenshan Hospital and thus marked the beginning of its operations.
YOU1000000002_S0000098	They started with just a few dozen patients, but in a matter of days, this ballooned to hundreds.
YOU1000000002_S0000099	Huoshenshan Hospital was only the start of China's plan to ramp up the number of available beds in Wuhan.
YOU1000000002_S0000100	Just three days after He Shunshan's opening, another, even larger hospital called Lei Shunshan opened.
YOU1000000002_S0000101	Its 1,600 beds and 32 wards were built in just 12 days.
YOU1000000002_S0000102	Meanwhile, other hospitals were converted to isolate and treat coronavirus patients, and stadiums and exhibition centers were turned into hospitals as well.
YOU1000000002_S0000103	Still, though, even with this swift, decisive action, reports indicate that many of those with milder cases of coronavirus are getting turned away from hospitals in Wuhan.
YOU1000000002_S0000104	It unfortunately seems that coronavirus, with its tremendous severity, is one of the few things that can outpace China.
YOU1000000002_S0000105	If you want to learn more about how viruses such as this work from a biological perspective, CuriosityStream has a fascinating short documentary on one previous epidemic.
YOU1000000002_S0000106	the Zika virus.
YOU1000000002_S0000107	There's plenty in there that applies to the current coronavirus outbreak, and this is just one of thousands of top-quality non-fiction shows and documentaries you can watch on CuriosityStream.
